{"title_page": "Yellow Submarine (film)", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2018}} \n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Yellow Submarine\n| image          = Beatles Yellow Submarine move poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Original theatrical release poster\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[George Dunning]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=The Encyclopedia of Animated Cartoons Third Edition|year=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=0-8160-6599-3}}</ref>\n* '''Animation:'''\n* [[Robert Balser]]\n* George Dunning\n* [[Jack Stokes (director)|Jack Stokes]]\n* '''Live-action:'''\n* Dennis Abey\n* [[Al Brodax]]\n}}\n| producer       = Al Brodax\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lee Minoff]]\n* Al Brodax\n* [[Jack Mendelsohn]]\n* [[Erich Segal]]\n* '''Uncredited:'''\n* [[Roger McGough]]<ref>[http://www.awn.com/mag/issue3.4/3.4pages/3.4cohen.html The Beatles' Yellow Submarine Turns 30] \"Edelmann is given credit for inventing the Blue Meanies to serve that role. In an interview, Edelman added yet another to those who contributed to the film's script. He said, \"There was never one script. We had about 20. Roger McGough was responsible for much of it.\" McGough was a Liverpool poet who was brought in to add a Liverpool flavour to the soundtrack. He was paid \u00a3500 for his work, but was not given screen credit.\" (Accessed 19 October 2014.)</ref>\n}}\n| story          = Lee Minoff\n| based on       = {{based on|\"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"|[[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Paul Angelis]]\n* [[John Clive]]\n* [[Dick Emery]]\n* [[Geoffrey Hughes|Geoff Hughes]]\n* [[Lance Percival]]\n}}\n| narrator      = Paul Angelis\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* Lennon\u2013McCartney\n* [[George Harrison]]\n* [[Ringo Starr]]\n* '''Musical Director:'''\n* [[George Martin]]\n}}\n| editing        = [[Brian J. Bishop]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Apple Corps|Apple Films]]\n* [[King Features Syndicate]]\n* TVC London\n}}\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1968|7|17|United Kingdom}}\n                   {{Film date|df=y|1968|11|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 87:35--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/yellow-submarine-1970-2 | title=''YELLOW SUBMARINE'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=3 July 1968 | accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom<br>United States<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/23964 |title=''YELLOW SUBMARINE'' |work=[[American Film Institute]]}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000\n}}\n'''''Yellow Submarine''''' (also known as '''''The Beatles: Yellow Submarine''''') is a 1968 British [[animated film]] inspired by the music of [[the Beatles]], directed by animation producer [[George Dunning]], and produced by [[United Artists]] and [[King Features Syndicate]]. Initial press reports stated that the Beatles themselves would provide their own character voices.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=196804272#/19680427/1 | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | title=Blue Meanie Battle | date=27 April 1968 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107041944/http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=196804272#/19680427/1 | archivedate=7 November 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, aside from composing and performing the songs, the real Beatles participated only in the closing scene of the film, while their cartoon counterparts were voiced by other actors.\n\nThe film received widespread acclaim from critics and audiences alike, in contrast to the Beatles' previous film venture ''[[Magical Mystery Tour (film)|Magical Mystery Tour]]''. [[Pixar]] co-founder and former chief creative officer [[John Lasseter]] has credited the film with bringing more interest in animation as a serious art form.<ref>[[John Lasseter|Lasseter, J.]] 2012.</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' commented that it \"turned into a smash hit, delighting [[Adolescence|adolescents]] and [[Aestheticism|aesthetes]] alike\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900461,00.html#ixzz1KsYGvLH2 | work=Time | title=Art: New Magic in Animation | date=27 December 1968}}</ref> Half a century after its release, it is still regarded as a landmark of animation.<ref name=\"Why the Beatles' Yellow Submarine is a Trippy Cult Classic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20180724-why-the-beatles-yellow-submarine-is-a-trippy-cult-classic |title=Why the Beatles' Yellow Submarine is a Trippy Cult Classic: Yellow Submarine is a delight that deserves greater recognition: Rumour has it, it's one of the Queen's favourite films, writes Holly Williams. |last=Williams |first=Holly |date=25 July 2018 |website=BBC |access-date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[John Lennon]] later said: \"I think it's a great movie, it's my favourite Beatle movie. [[Sean Lennon|Sean]] loves it now, all the little children love it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.youtube.com/watch?v=LcXEQZs1dcg |title=John Lennon 1980 Interview |work=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nPepperland is a cheerful, music-loving [[paradise]] under the sea, home to [[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]. The titular Yellow Submarine rests on an [[Mesoamerican pyramids|Aztec-like pyramid]] on a hill. At the edge of the land is a range of high blue mountains.\n\nThe land falls under a surprise attack from the music-hating [[Blue Meanies (Yellow Submarine)|Blue Meanies]], who live beyond the mountains. The attack starts with a music-proof glass globe that imprisons the band. The Blue Meanies fire projectiles and drop apples (a reference to the Beatles' then-new company [[Apple Corps]])<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=_TP3DAAAQBAJ|title=The Encyclopedia of Musicians and Bands on Film|last=Melissa U. D. Goldsmith, Paige A. Willson, Anthony J. Fonseca|first=|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2016|isbn=978-1442269866|location=|pages=348}}</ref> that render Pepperland's residents immobile as statues, and drain the entire countryside of colour.\n\nIn the last minutes before his capture, Pepperland's elderly Lord Mayor sends Old Fred, an aging sailor, to get help. Fred takes off in the Yellow Submarine (\"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"). He travels to [[Liverpool]] (\"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\"), where he follows a depressed [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]] to \"The Pier\", a house-like building on the top of a hill, and persuades him to return to Pepperland with him. Ringo collects his \"mates\" [[John Lennon|John]], [[George Harrison|George]], and [[Paul McCartney|Paul]], and the five journey back to Pepperland in the submarine. As they operate the submarine, they sing \"[[All Together Now]]\", after which they pass through several regions on their way to Pepperland, including the Sea of Time, where time flows both forwards and backwards (\"[[When I'm Sixty-Four]]\"); the Sea of Science (\"[[Only a Northern Song]]\"); and the Sea of Monsters, where Ringo is rescued from monsters after being ejected from the submarine. In the Sea of Nothing, the protagonists meet [[Jeremy Hillary Boob]] Ph.D., a short and studious creature (\"[[Nowhere Man (song)|Nowhere Man]]\"). As they prepare to leave, Ringo feels sorry for the lonely Boob, and invites him to join them aboard the submarine. They arrive at the Foothills of the Headlands, where they are separated from the submarine and Old Fred (\"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\"). They then find themselves in the Sea of Holes, an expanse of flat surfaces with many holes. Jeremy is kidnapped by a Blue Meanie, and the group finds their way to Pepperland.\n\nReuniting with Old Fred and reviving the Lord Mayor, they look upon the now-miserable, grey landscape. The Beatles dress up as Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band and steal some instruments. The four rally the land to rebellion (\"[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (song)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]\"). The [[Chief Blue Meanie]] retaliates by sending out the Dreadful Flying Glove, but John defeats by singing (\"[[All You Need is Love]]\"). Pepperland is restored to colour as its flowers re-bloom and its residents revive. The original Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band are released, and join the Beatles in combating the Meanies' multi-headed dog (\"[[Hey Bulldog]]\"). Jeremy performs some \"transformation magic\" on the Chief Blue Meanie, causing the Meanie to bloom roses and sadly concede defeat. John extends an offer of friendship, and the Chief Blue Meanie has a change of heart and accepts. An enormous party ensues (\"[[It's All Too Much]]\").\n\nThe real Beatles then appear in [[live-action]], and playfully show off souvenirs from the events of the film. George has the submarine's motor, Paul has \"a little 'love'\", and Ringo has \"half a hole\" in his pocket (having supposedly given the other half to Jeremy). Ringo points out John looking through a telescope, which prompts Paul to ask what he sees. John replies that \"newer and bluer Meanies have been sighted within the vicinity of this theatre\" and claims there is only one way to go out: \"Singing!\" The four oblige with a short reprise of \"All Together Now\", which ends with translations of the song's title in various languages appearing in sequence on the screen.\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[John Clive]] as [[John Lennon|John]]\n* [[Geoffrey Hughes]] as [[Paul McCartney|Paul]]\n* Peter Batten as [[George Harrison|George]] ''(uncredited)''\n* [[Paul Angelis]] as Opening Narrator / [[Chief Blue Meanie]] / [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]] / George ''(additional dialogue)''\n* [[Dick Emery]] as Max / Lord Mayor / [[Jeremy Hillary Boob]]\n* [[Lance Percival]] as \"Young/Old\" Fred\n\n'''<small>Sources:<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0063823/fullcredits#cast Yellow Submarine (1968) \u2013 Full cast and crew<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[[Apple Corps]], 2012.</ref></small>'''\n\n'''Cast notes'''\n* According to the special features section of the ''Yellow Submarine'' home media release, Peter Batten provided the voice of George for about the first half of the film. Before he finished recording for the film, he was discovered to be a [[deserter]] from the [[British Army of the Rhine]] in [[West Germany]], and was arrested. His part was completed by Angelis, who was also the voice of Ringo and the Chief Blue Meanie.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/1999/aug/24/artsfeatures2|last=Espiner|first=Mark|title=The Fake Four | location=London |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 August 1999|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Percival also provided the voices of Paul and Ringo for the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] TV cartoon series ''[[The Beatles (TV series)|The Beatles]]''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[The Beatles]] were not enthusiastic about participating in a new motion picture, having been dissatisfied with their second feature film, ''[[Help! (film)|Help!]]'' (1965), directed by [[Richard Lester]]. However, they saw an animated film as a favourable way to complete their commitment to [[United Artists]] for a third film. Many fans have assumed that the cartoon did not satisfy the contract, but ''[[Let It Be (film)|Let It Be]]'' (1970) was the film not connected to the original three-picture deal.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hieronimus|first1=Dr Robert|title=Inside the Yellow Submarine|publisher=Krause|isbn=0-87349-360-5|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\nThe Beatles make a live-action [[cameo appearance]] in the final scene, which was filmed on 25 January 1968, shortly before the band's [[The Beatles in India|trip to India]]. This was done primarily to fulfill their contractual obligation to United Artists to actually appear in the film. The cameo was originally intended to feature a post-production psychedelic background and effects, but because of time and budget constraints, a blank, black background remained in the final film. While Starr and McCartney still looked the same as their animated counterparts, Lennon's and Harrison's physical appearances had changed by the time the cameo was shot. Both were clean-shaven, and Lennon had begun to grow his hair longer with accompanying mutton-chop [[sideburns]].\n\nThe original story was written by Lee Minoff, based on the song by John Lennon and Paul McCartney, and the screenplay was penned by four collaborators including [[Erich Segal]]. George Harrison's character's recurring line \"It's all in the mind\" is taken from ''[[The Goon Show]]''.\n\nAs with many motion-picture [[Musical film|musicals]], the music takes precedence over the actual plot, and most of the story is a series of [[set piece]]s designed to present Beatles music set to various images, in a form reminiscent of [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' (and foreshadowing the rise of music videos and MTV thirteen years later). {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Nonetheless, the film still presents a modern-day [[fairy tale]] representing the values of its intended [[hippie]] audience.\n\nThe dialogue is littered with [[pun]]s, [[double entendre]]s and Beatles in-jokes. In the DVD [[Audio commentary|commentary track]], production supervisor John Coates states that many of these lines were written by Liverpudlian poet [[Roger McGough]], though he received no credit in the film.\n\nIn the DVD commentary track, Coates states that the Meanies were always intended to be coloured blue. However, Millicent McMillan recalls that the Blue Meanies were originally supposed to be red, or even purple, but when [[Heinz Edelmann]]'s assistant accidentally changed the colours, the film's characters took on a different meaning.<ref name=\"Hieronimus-hidden\">{{cite web | last = Hieronimus | first = Robert R. | date = 11 September 1999 | url = http://www.21stcenturyradio.com/yellowsub/billboard.html | title = The Hidden Stories Behind Yellow Submarine | work = Billboard | accessdate = 19 April 2009}}</ref> Coates acknowledges in the commentary that the \"are you Bluish? You don't look Bluish\" joke in the film is a pun on the then-contemporary expression \"you don't look Jewish\", but that it was not intended to be derogatory.\n\n===Animation===\nThe Beatles' animated personas were based on their appearance in the promotional film for the song \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\", with the exception of Paul being without his moustache. The film also includes several references to songs not included in the soundtrack, including \"[[A Day in the Life]]\", the lyrics of which are referenced in the \"Sea of Holes\" scene; the orchestral breaks earlier in the film are also taken from the song.\n\nNational and foreign animators were assembled by TVC. American animators [[Robert Balser]] and [[Jack Stokes (director)|Jack Stokes]] were hired as the film's animation directors.<ref name=awn>{{cite news|first=Jennifer|last=Wolfe|title='Yellow Submarine' Animation Director Robert Balser Passes at 88 |url=http://www.awn.com/news/yellow-submarine-animation-director-robert-balser-passes-88  |work=[[Animation World Network]] |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=thr>{{cite news|first=Mike|last=Barnes|title=Robert Balser, Animation Director on 'Yellow Submarine,' Dies at 88 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/robert-balser-dead-yellow-submarine-852980  |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=7 January 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Charlie Jenkins, one of the film's key creative directors, was responsible for the entire \"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\" sequence, as well as the submarine travel from Liverpool, through London, to splashdown. Jenkins also was responsible for \"Only a Northern Song\" in the Sea of Science, plus much of the multi-image sequences. A large crew of skilled animators, including (in alphabetical order) Alan Ball, [[Ron Campbell (animator)|Ron Campbell]], John Challis, Hester Coblentz, Geoff Collins, Rich Cox, Duane Crowther, Tony Cuthbert, Malcolm Draper, [[Paul Driessen (animator)|Paul Driessen]], Cam Ford, Norm Drew, Tom Halley, Dick Horne, Arthur Humberstone, Dennis Hunt, [[Greg Irons]], [[Dianne Jackson]], [[Anne Jolliffe]], Dave Livesey, Reg Lodge, Geoff Loynes, Lawrence Moorcroft, Ted Percival, Mike Pocock, [[Gerald Potterton]], and Peter Tupy, were responsible for bringing the animated Beatles to life. The background work was executed by artists under the direction of [[Alison de Vere]] and Millicent McMillan, who were both background supervisors. Ted Lewis and Chris Miles were responsible for animation cleanup.\n\n[[George Dunning]], who also worked on [[The Beatles (TV series)|the Beatles cartoon series]], was the overall director for the film, supervising over 200 artists for 11 months. \"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\" was Dunning's idea, which he turned over to Bill Sewell, who delivered more than thirty minutes of [[Rotoscoping|rotoscoped]] images. By that time, Dunning was unavailable, and Bob Balser, with the help of Arne Gustafson, edited the material to its sequence length in the film.\n\nThe animation design of ''Yellow Submarine'' has sometimes been incorrectly attributed to famous psychedelic [[pop art]] artist of the era [[Peter Max]], but the film's art director was [[Heinz Edelmann]]. Edelmann, along with his contemporary [[Milton Glaser]], pioneered the psychedelic style for which Max would later become famous, but according to Edelmann and producer Al Brodax, as quoted in the book ''Inside the Yellow Submarine'' by Hieronimus and Cortner, Max had nothing to do with the production of ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref name=\"Hieronimus-inside\">{{Cite book | last =Hieronimus | first =Robert |author2=Laura Cortner | title =Inside the Yellow Submarine | year =2002 | publisher =Krause Publications | location =Iola, Wisconsin, USA | isbn =0-87349-360-5 | page =81 | chapter =| chapterurl =| quote =}}</ref>\n \nEdelmann's surreal visual style contrasts greatly with the efforts of [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] and other animated Hollywood films that had been previously released at the time. The film uses a style of [[limited animation]]. It also paved the way for [[Terry Gilliam]]'s animations for ''[[Do Not Adjust Your Set]]'' and ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' (particularly the ''Eleanor Rigby'' sequence), as well as the ''[[Schoolhouse Rock]]'' vignettes for ABC and similar-looking animation in early seasons of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' and ''[[The Electric Company]]''. (Only one of the animation staff of ''Yellow Submarine'', Ron Campbell, contributed subsequent animation to  [[Sesame Workshop|Children's Television Workshop]].)\n\n===Music===\nIn addition to the 1966 title song \"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\", several complete or excerpted songs, four previously unreleased, were used in the film. The songs included \"[[All Together Now]]\", \"[[It's All Too Much]]\" (written by Harrison), \"[[Baby, You're a Rich Man]]\" (which had first appeared as the [[B-side]] to \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\" in June 1967), \"[[Only a Northern Song]]\" (a Harrison composition originally recorded during sessions for ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]])'' and \"[[Hey Bulldog]]\". Written by Lennon, this last track was cut from the film before it opened in the US. \"Hey Bulldog\" was restored for the US theatrical and home video reissue in 1999. The four new songs used on the soundtrack album were not considered of high enough quality for appearance on a \"regular\" Beatles album.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nThe film's instrumental music was an orchestral score composed and arranged by [[George Martin]]. One of the film's cues, heard after the main title credits, was originally recorded during sessions for \"[[Good Night (Beatles song)|Good Night]]\" (a track on ''[[The Beatles (album)|The Beatles]]'', also known as the \"White Album\") and would have been used as the introduction to Ringo Starr's White Album composition \"[[Don't Pass Me By]]\". The same cue was later released as \"[[A Beginning]]\" on the 1996 Beatles compilation ''[[Anthology 3]]''.\n\n==Musical numbers==\n:All tracks written by [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]] except where noted.\n\n:Track start and end time is indicated in [[hour|hrs]]:[[minute|mins]]:[[second|secs]]. These are approximated because the songs are embedded in the film plot and cannot be strictly separated.\n\n# 0:00:21\u20130:02:15: \"Introduction Story\" music by [[George Martin]]\n# 0:07:55\u20130:10:40: \"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"\n# 0:10:40\u20130:13:30: \"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\"\n# 0:19:00\u20130:19:55: \"[[Love You To]]\" ([[George Harrison]]) (excerpt, played during George's entrance)\n# 0:22:30\u20130:23:05: \"[[A Day in the Life]]\" (excerpt, orchestral swell, starting as the submarine takes off)\n# 0:23:25\u20130:25:55: \"[[All Together Now]]\"\n# 0:28:20\u20130:31:15: \"[[When I'm Sixty-Four]]\"\n# 0:31:30\u20130:34:30: \"[[Only a Northern Song]]\" (Harrison)\n# 0:43:15\u20130:46:15: \"[[Nowhere Man (song)|Nowhere Man]]\"\n# 0:48:00\u20130:51:30: \"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\"\n# 0:54:30\u20130:54:50: \"Yellow Submarine\" (a short vocal excerpt when Ringo finds the green hole that leads to Pepperland)\n# 0:56:15\u20130:56:25: \"[[Think for Yourself]]\" (Harrison) (short excerpt, a line is sung [[a cappella]] to revive the Lord Mayor)\n# 1:06:35\u20131:08:50: \"[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (song)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]\"\n# 1:08:50\u20131:09:05: \"[[With a Little Help from My Friends]]\" (short excerpt, directly following \"Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band\" without interruption, just as on the [[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|1967 album of the same name]])\n# 1:11:45\u20131:15:05: \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\"\n# 1:16:30\u20131:16:40: \"[[Baby, You're a Rich Man]]\" (excerpt, played as Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band are, thanks to Ringo's \"hole in [his] pocket\", set free from the anti-music bubble; the recording of the song is expanded for the American-released version, and the scene with the expansion of the recording of the song leads to a scene that replaces the anti-climactic \"Hey Bulldog\".){{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n# 1:17:25\u20131:21:00: \"[[Hey Bulldog]]\" (originally shown only in Europe before the film's 1999 restoration)\n# 1:24:15\u20131:27:15: \"[[It's All Too Much]]\" (Harrison)\n# 1:27:15\u20131:29:00: \"[[All Together Now]]\" (accompanied by images of the real Beatles singing, numbers and letters, and \"all together now\" translated in various languages)\n\n;First soundtrack album\n{{Main|Yellow Submarine (album)}}\nThe original soundtrack album comprised the four new Beatles songs, two other Beatles songs (the title song and \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\"), and orchestral pieces by [[George Martin]].\n\nThe orchestral pieces were also used in the short [[NASA]] ''[[Apollo 9]]'' mission films, which NASA made for every mission.<ref>{{Citation|title=Apollo 9 : space duet of SpiderGumdrop|url=http://archive.org/details/Apollo9SpaceDuetOfSpidergumdrop|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>\n\n;Second soundtrack album\n{{Main|Yellow Submarine Songtrack}}\nAnother soundtrack was released in 1999 that contained all of the Beatles' songs from the film except \"A Day in the Life\".\n\n==Reception==\n''Yellow Submarine'' received widespread critical acclaim. Released in the midst of the [[Psychedelia|psychedelic]] pop culture of the 1960s, the film drew in moviegoers both for its lush, wildly creative images and its soundtrack of Beatles songs. The film was distributed worldwide by [[United Artists]] in two versions. The version shown in [[Europe]] included an extra musical number, \"Hey Bulldog\", heard in the final third of the film. For release in the United States, the number was replaced with alternative animation because of time constraints. It was felt that, at the time, American audiences would grow tired from the length of the film. Despite the Beatles connection, the film was not a commercial success.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Silver |first1=David |title=The Compleat Beatles DVD |work=The Compleat Beatles |agency=Delilah Films, Inc. |issue=First release |publisher=MGM/UA Entertainment Co. |date=1982}}</ref>\nThe film realized receipts of more than $992,000 USD in the US and more than $280,000 USD internationally.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine - Financial Information |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Yellow-Submarine#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1896121857/weekend/ |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDB.com |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> For reference, the top-grossing films for 1968 were in excess of $50M in the domestic market alone.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Funny Girl (1968) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Funny-Girl-%281968%29#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=2001: a space odyssey |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/2001-A-Space-Odyssey#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Informatioon Services, LLC |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film currently holds a 97% approval rating based on 58 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9/10.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beatles_the_yellow_submarine |website=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The website's critical consensus states: \"A joyful, phantasmagoric blend of colorful animation and the music of the Beatles, ''Yellow Submarine'' is delightful (and occasionally melancholy) family fare.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beatles_the_yellow_submarine/ | title =Yellow Submarine (1968) | publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate =29 June 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 78 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/yellow-submarine |title=Yellow Submarine Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rights and distribution==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nOf all the Beatles films released by United Artists, ''Yellow Submarine'' been the only one to which UA retained the rights, leading up to its purchase by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1981. In 2005, [[Sony Pictures|Sony Pictures Entertainment]] led a consortium that purchased MGM and UA. SPE handled theatrical distribution for MGM until 2012. [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] was responsible for home video distribution when the most recent home video release went out of print.\n\nFor the 50th anniversary of the movie in 2018, it was screened in the UK and Ireland for one day on 8 July 2018, and in the US from 8 July 2018.<ref name=\"Jon Blistein\">{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-beatles-yellow-submarine-returning-to-theaters-630183/ | work=Rolling Stone | author=Jon Blistein | title=The Beatles' 'Yellow Submarine' Returning to Theaters | date=4 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/iconic-beatles-film-heading-back-uk-cinemas-one-night-2219667 | work=Rolling Stone | author= Nick Reilly| title=This iconic Beatles film is heading back to UK cinemas for its 50th anniversary| date=15 January 2018}}</ref> [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] negotiated exclusive streaming rights to the film via its [[Prime Video]] service, starting 13 July 2018 in the UK, the US, Canada, Germany, Spain, France and Italy under a deal with [[Apple Corps]]. The companies declined to disclose the length of Amazon's exclusive rights.<ref name=\"Todd Spangler\">{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/beatles-yellow-submarine-amazon-prime-video-1202872708/ | work=Variety| author=  Todd Spangler| title=The Beatles' 'Yellow Submarine' Now Streaming Exclusively on Amazon Prime Video| date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nWith the dawn of the home-video era came an opportunity to release ''Yellow Submarine'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]]. However, it was held up by United Artists for some years over music-rights issues.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Coinciding with the [[Compact disc|CD]] release of the soundtrack album, United Artists issued the film on home video on 28 August, 1987. To the disappointment of fans in the UK, the film was presented in its US theatrical version, thereby omitting the \"Hey Bulldog\" scene.<ref>{{cite book|first=Keith|last=Badman|year=2001|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-7119-8307-6|pp=390\u201391}}</ref> The video was discontinued around 1990, and for many years copies of the original VHS issue were considered [[collectable]]s.\n\nOn 14 September 1999, then-rights holders [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and Apple reissued the film for the first time on [[DVD]] and VHS using restoration techniques of the time. The sound was remixed to [[Dolby 5.1]], and the film was re-edited to its European theatrical version, with the \"Hey Bulldog\" number restored. This version (released through MGM Home Entertainment) went out of print once the rights reverted to Apple Corps.\n\n===Restoration===\nOn 20 March 2012, Apple Corps announced that the film had been restored by hand for [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] release on 28 May 2012 (29 May in North America), later delayed one week to 4 June 2012 (5 June in North America). The company stated: \"The film's soundtrack album will be reissued on CD on the same date. The film has been restored in 4K digital resolution for the first time \u2013 all done by hand, frame by frame.\" The delicate restoration was supervised by Paul Rutan Jr and his team, which included Chris Dusendschon, Rayan Raghuram and Randy Walker.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Re-release of Yellow Submarine \u2013 Exclusive Q & A with Paul Rutan Jr.|url = http://www.21stcenturyradio.com/yellowsub/PaulRutanJr_Hieronimus_Restoring_Yellow_Sub.html|website = 21stcenturyradio|accessdate = 28 May 2015}}</ref> No automated software was used to clean up the film's repaired and digitised photo-chemical elements. The work was done by hand, a single frame at a time, by 40 to 60 trained digital artists, over several months.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Yellow Submarine Gets a Film Restoration and 4K Remaster|url = http://www.studiodaily.com/2012/06/yellow-submarine-gets-a-film-restoration-and-4k-remaster/|website = Studio Daily|accessdate = 28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the DVD and Blu-ray re-release, the restored version also received a limited theatrical run in May 2012.\n\nFor the 50th anniversary of the film, the soundtrack and score were remixed in 5.1 stereo surround sound at [[Abbey Road Studios]] by mix engineer Peter Cobbin.<ref name=\"Jon Blistein\"/>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}{{main|Yellow Submarine (album)}}\nOn 14 September 1999, United Artists and [[Apple Records]] digitally remixed the audio of the film for a highly successful theatrical and home video re-release. Though the visuals were not digitally restored, a new transfer was done after cleaning the original film negative and rejuvenating the colour. A [[Yellow Submarine Songtrack|soundtrack album for this version]] was also released, which featured the first extensive digital stereo remixes of Beatles material.\n\nThe previous DVD release also featured a music-only audio track, without spoken dialogue, leaving only the music and the songs.\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\n* [[1968 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]] Special Award\n* 1969 [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation|Best Dramatic Presentation]] (nominated)\n* 1970 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Original Score Written for a Motion Picture or a Television Special]] (nominated)\n\n== Cancelled remake ==\nIn August 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Walt Disney Pictures]] and filmmaker [[Robert Zemeckis]] were negotiating to produce a [[3D film|3D]] [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[remake]] of the film. [[Motion capture]] was to be used, as with Zemeckis' previous animated films ''[[The Polar Express (film)|The Polar Express]]'' (2004), ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'' (2006), ''[[Beowulf (2007 film)|Beowulf]]'' (2007) and ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' (2009). ''Variety'' also indicated that Disney hoped to release the film in time for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]].<ref>Fleming, Michael. \"[https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118007485?refCatId=13 Disney, Zemeckis to board 'Submarine']\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', 19 August 2009.</ref> Disney and Apple Corps officially announced the remake at the inaugural D23 Expo on 11 September 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonzone.net/news/articles/31091/disney-and-apple-corps-ltd.-confirm-yellow-submarine-remake |title=Animation News Discussion Cartoon Community \u2013 toonzone news |publisher=News.toonzone.net |accessdate=9 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913104045/http://www.toonzone.net/2009/09/disney-and-apple-corps-ltd-confirm-yellow-submarine-remake/%23.UFG4GqjLdRw |archivedate=13 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\nComedian [[Peter Serafinowicz]] was cast to voice Paul, [[Dean Lennox Kelly]] as John, [[Cary Elwes]] as George and [[Adam Campbell (actor)|Adam Campbell]] as Ringo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=26687 |title=Peter Serafinowicz IS Paul McCartney! |work=Empire  |accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref> California-based Beatles [[Tribute act|tribute band]] [[The Fab Four (tribute)|The Fab Four]] was cast to perform the performance capture animation for the animated Beatles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/01/12/actors-tribute-band-cast-as-beatles-in-zemeckis-yellow-submarine-remake/ |title=Actors, Tribute Band Cast as Beatles in Zemeckis' \"Yellow Submarine\" Remake |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |work=Rolling Stone |date=12 January 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117024516/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/01/12/actors-tribute-band-cast-as-beatles-in-zemeckis-yellow-submarine-remake/ |archivedate=17 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gibson.com/en%2Dus/Lifestyle/News/yellow%2Dsubmarine%2D0113/ | title=Main Cast Selected For Beatles' Yellow Submarine Remake | first=Russell | last=Hall | publisher=gibson.com | date=13 January 2010 | accessdate=13 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603235918/http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/News/yellow-submarine-0113/ | archivedate=3 June 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Disney closed Zemeckis' digital film studio [[ImageMovers|ImageMovers Digital]] after unsatisfactory box-office performance of ''A Christmas Carol''.<ref name=\"gump\" /> On 14 March 2011, Disney abandoned the project, citing the disastrous opening weekend results of [[Simon Wells]]' ''[[Mars Needs Moms]]''. Criticism toward motion-capture technology was also a factor.<ref name=\"gump\">Kit, Borys. [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/15/us-yellowsubmarine-idUSTRE72E0ED20110315 Disney torpedoes Zemeckis' \"Yellow Submarine\"] ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' (14 March 2011).</ref>\n\nAfter its cancellation at Disney, Zemeckis tried to pitch the remake to other studios. By December 2012, Zemeckis expressed that he had lost interest in the project, stating: \"That would have been great to bring the Beatles back to life. But it's probably better not to be remade \u2013 you're always behind the 8-ball when do you{{sic}} a remake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.slashfilm.com/robert-zemeckis-gives-up-on-the-yellow-submarine-remake/|title= Robert Zemeckis Gives Up On the 'Yellow Submarine' Remake|work=Slash Film|last1=Han|first1=Angie|date=27 December 2012|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:Corgi Classics Beatles Yellow Submarine 1999.jpg|thumb|In the late 1960s, Corgi Classics Ltd. (formerly known as Corgi Toys) issued a licensed die-cast toy model of Yellow Submarine. In 1999, this particular model was re-issued as a collector\u2019s item (as shown).]]\n* In the 1993 episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' titled \"[[Last Exit to Springfield]]\", [[Lisa Simpson]], under [[anesthetic]], has a dream sequence highly reminiscent of the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Erickson|first=Hal|year=2005|title=Television Cartoon Shows: An Illustrated Encyclopedia, 1949\u20142003|volume=2|edition=2nd|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|page=746|isbn=978-0-7864-2099-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/28/arts/television/simpsons-history-season-30-timeline.html|title='The Simpsons' at 30: Six Era-Defining Episodes|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|date=28 September 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-simpsons-oral-history-of-last-exit-to-springfield-the-best-episode-ever/|title='The Simpsons' Oral History of 'Last Exit to Springfield,' The Best Episode Ever|last=Welk|first=Brian|date=8 March 2018|website=[[TheWrap]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Professional wrestler [[The Blue Meanie]] derived his name and persona from the villains of the film.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Oliver|first1=Greg|last2=Johnson|first2=Steven|year=2019|title=The Pro Wrestling Hall of Fame: The Storytellers (From the Terrible Turk to Twitter)|publisher=[[ECW Press]]|isbn=978-1770415027}}</ref>\n* The 2001 episode of ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' titled \"Meet the Beat Alls\", which contains numerous Beatles references, briefly features cameos of the band members' likenesses from ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/dont-beat/|title=If That Don't Beat All|last=Mallory|first=Michael|date=2 January 2014|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2007 film ''[[Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story]]'' features an animated acid trip sequence that parodies ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/ae/2007/12/20/Movie-Review-The-Dewey-Cox-Story/stories/200712200360|title=Movie Review: 'The Dewey Cox Story'|last=Vancheri|first=Barbara|date=20 December 2007|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/03/movies/yellow-submarine-beatles-50th-anniversary.html|title='Yellow Submarine' to Arrive in Theaters for Its 50th Anniversary|last=Chow|first=Andrew R.|date=3 April 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Olson|first=Christopher J.|year=2018|title=100 Greatest Cult Films|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|page=257|isbn=978-1442208223}}</ref>\n* The third ''[[Futurama]]'' film, ''[[Futurama: Bender's Game|Bender's Game]]'' (2008), makes visual references to ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/futurama-bender-s-game-1798184766|title=Futurama: Bender's Game|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=3 September 2015|work=[[The A. V. Club]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2014, apparel company [[Vans]] released a series of shoes based on ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-beatles-team-with-vans-for-yellow-submarine-shoes-242240/|title=The Beatles Team With Vans for 'Yellow Submarine' Shoes|last=Grow|first=Kory|date=23 January 2014|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2016, for the 50th anniversary of the original song's release, the die-cast toy car brand [[Hot Wheels]] released a miniature replica of the Yellow Submarine from the film, as well as an assortment of six toy cars featuring imagery from the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/06/08/beatles-yellow-submarine-50th-anniversary-hot-wheels/|title=Hot Wheels unveil Beatles' Yellow Submarine 50th anniversary collection \u2014 exclusive|last=Slead|first=Evan|date=8 June 2016|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2016, [[Lego Ideas]] released a ''Yellow Submarine'' Lego set that includes minifigures of the four Beatles and Jeremy Hillary Boob, along with the submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-beatles/97065|title=Lego unveil new Yellow Submarine set with The Beatles|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|date=12 October 2016|website=[[NME]]|access-date=25 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015034333/https://www.nme.com/news/the-beatles/97065|archive-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n*In the 2019 [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'', [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony Stark]] jokingly refers to his shipmate [[Nebula (comics)|Nebula]] as a \"Blue Meanie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/4/30/18619514/avengers-endgame-22-little-moments-that-added-up-to-greatness|title='Avengers: Endgame': 22 little moments that added up to greatness|last=Roeper|first=Richard|author-link=Richard Roeper|date=30 April 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/04/avengers-endgame-easter-eggs.html|title=An Exhaustive List of All the Easter Eggs and Comic Book References in Avengers: Endgame|last=Grebey|first=James|date=29 April 2019|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Animation|Film}}\n* [[The Beatles in film]]\n* [[List of animated feature-length films]]\n* [[List of fictional ships#Film|List of fictional submarines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.thebeatles.com/film/yellow-submarine}}\n* {{IMDb title|0063823|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{tcmdb title|96403|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|beatles_the_yellow_submarine|Yellow Submarine}}\n* [https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-yellow-submarine-1968 ''Yellow Submarine'' movie review] by [[Roger Ebert]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/brunel/A295562 h2g2 Yellow Submarine \u2013 the Film Edited Guide Entry]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/23/arts/design/23edelmann.html \"Heinz Edelmann, 'Yellow Submarine' Artist, Dies at 75\"], ''The New York Times''\n* [https://www.popmatters.com/pm/post/110163-its-all-too-much-robert-zemeckis-proposed-yellow-submarine-remake/ Proposed ''Yellow Submarine'' remake]\n\n{{Yellow Submarine}}\n{{Beatles filmography and videography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yellow Submarine}}\n[[Category:The Beatles' Yellow Submarine]]\n[[Category:1968 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1968 animated films]]\n[[Category:1960s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:British musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:British musical films]]\n[[Category:Animation based on real people]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:British rock music films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Beatles]]\n[[Category:Films associated with the Beatles]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of The Beatles]]\n[[Category:Films based on songs]]\n[[Category:Films set in a fictional country]]\n[[Category:Films set in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Rotoscoped films]]\n[[Category:Submarine films]]\n[[Category:Apple Films films]]\n[[Category:United Artists animated films]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Psychedelia]]\n[[Category:British animated films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2018}} \n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Yellow Submarine\n| image          = Beatles Yellow Submarine move poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Original theatrical release poster\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[George Dunning]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=The Encyclopedia of Animated Cartoons Third Edition|year=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=0-8160-6599-3}}</ref>\n* '''Animation:'''\n* [[Robert Balser]]\n* George Dunning\n* [[Jack Stokes (director)|Jack Stokes]]\n* '''Live-action:'''\n* Dennis Abey\n* [[Al Brodax]]\n}}\n| producer       = Al Brodax\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lee Minoff]]\n* Al Brodax\n* [[Jack Mendelsohn]]\n* [[Erich Segal]]\n* '''Uncredited:'''\n* [[Roger McGough]]<ref>[http://www.awn.com/mag/issue3.4/3.4pages/3.4cohen.html The Beatles' Yellow Submarine Turns 30] \"Edelmann is given credit for inventing the Blue Meanies to serve that role. In an interview, Edelman added yet another to those who contributed to the film's script. He said, \"There was never one script. We had about 20. Roger McGough was responsible for much of it.\" McGough was a Liverpool poet who was brought in to add a Liverpool flavour to the soundtrack. He was paid \u00a3500 for his work, but was not given screen credit.\" (Accessed 19 October 2014.)</ref>\n}}\n| story          = Lee Minoff\n| based on       = {{based on|\"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"|[[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Paul Angelis]]\n* [[John Clive]]\n* [[Dick Emery]]\n* [[Geoffrey Hughes|Geoff Hughes]]\n* [[Lance Percival]]\n}}\n| narrator      = Paul Angelis\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* Lennon\u2013McCartney\n* [[George Harrison]]\n* [[Ringo Starr]]\n* '''Musical Director:'''\n* [[George Martin]]\n}}\n| editing        = [[Brian J. Bishop]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Apple Corps|Apple Films]]\n* [[King Features Syndicate]]\n* TVC London\n}}\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1968|7|17|United Kingdom}}\n                   {{Film date|df=y|1968|11|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 87:35--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/yellow-submarine-1970-2 | title=''YELLOW SUBMARINE'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=3 July 1968 | accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom<br>United States<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/23964 |title=''YELLOW SUBMARINE'' |work=[[American Film Institute]]}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]250,000\n}}\n'''''Yellow Submarine''''' (also known as '''''The Beatles: Yellow Submarine''''') is a 1968 British animated [[fantasy film|film]] inspired by the music of [[the Beatles]], directed by animation producer [[George Dunning]], and produced by [[United Artists]] and [[King Features Syndicate]]. Initial press reports stated that the Beatles themselves would provide their own character voices.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=196804272#/19680427/1 | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | title=Blue Meanie Battle | date=27 April 1968 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107041944/http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=196804272#/19680427/1 | archivedate=7 November 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, aside from composing and performing the songs, the real Beatles participated only in the closing scene of the film, while their cartoon counterparts were voiced by other actors.\n\nThe film received widespread acclaim from critics and audiences alike, in contrast to the Beatles' previous film venture [[Magical Mystery Tour (film) | Magical Mystery Tour]]. [[Pixar]] co-founder and former chief creative officer [[John Lasseter]] has credited the film with bringing more interest in animation as a serious art form.<ref>[[John Lasseter|Lasseter, J.]] 2012.</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' commented that it \"turned into a smash hit, delighting [[Adolescence|adolescents]] and [[Aestheticism|aesthetes]] alike\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900461,00.html#ixzz1KsYGvLH2 | work=Time | title=Art: NEW MAGIC IN ANIMATION | date=27 December 1968}}</ref> Half a century after its release, it is still regarded as a landmark of animation.<ref name=\"Why the Beatles' Yellow Submarine is a Trippy Cult Classic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20180724-why-the-beatles-yellow-submarine-is-a-trippy-cult-classic |title=Why the Beatles' Yellow Submarine is a Trippy Cult Classic: Yellow Submarine is a delight that deserves greater recognition: Rumour has it, it's one of the Queen's favourite films, writes Holly Williams. |last=Williams |first=Holly |date=25 July 2018 |website=BBC |access-date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[John Lennon]] later said: \"I think it's a great movie, it's my favourite Beatle movie. [[Sean Lennon|Sean]] loves it now, all the little children love it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.youtube.com/watch?v=LcXEQZs1dcg |title=John Lennon 1980 Interview |work=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nPepperland is a cheerful, music-loving [[paradise]] under the sea, home to [[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]. The titular Yellow Submarine rests on an [[Mesoamerican pyramids|Aztec-like pyramid]] on a hill. At the edge of the land is a range of high blue mountains.\n\nThe land falls under a surprise attack from the music-hating [[Blue Meanies (Yellow Submarine)|Blue Meanies]], who live beyond the mountains. The attack starts with a music-proof glass globe that imprisons the band. The Blue Meanies fire projectiles and drop apples (a reference to the Beatles' then-new company [[Apple Corps]])<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=_TP3DAAAQBAJ|title=The Encyclopedia of Musicians and Bands on Film|last=Melissa U. D. Goldsmith, Paige A. Willson, Anthony J. Fonseca|first=|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2016|isbn=978-1442269866|location=|pages=348}}</ref> that render Pepperland's residents immobile as statues, and drain the entire countryside of colour.\n\nIn the last minutes before his capture, Pepperland's elderly Lord Mayor sends Old Fred, an aging sailor, to get help. Fred takes off in the Yellow Submarine (\"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"). He travels to [[Liverpool]] (\"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\"), where he follows a depressed [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]] to \"The Pier\", a house-like building on the top of a hill, and persuades him to return to Pepperland with him. Ringo collects his \"mates\" [[John Lennon|John]], [[George Harrison|George]], and [[Paul McCartney|Paul]], and the five journey back to Pepperland in the submarine. As they operate the submarine, they sing \"[[All Together Now]]\", after which they pass through several regions on their way to Pepperland, including the Sea of Time, where time flows both forwards and backwards (\"[[When I'm Sixty-Four]]\"); the Sea of Science (\"[[Only a Northern Song]]\"); and the Sea of Monsters, where Ringo is rescued from monsters after being ejected from the submarine. In the Sea of Nothing, the protagonists meet [[Jeremy Hillary Boob]] Ph.D., a short and studious creature (\"[[Nowhere Man (song)|Nowhere Man]]\"). As they prepare to leave, Ringo feels sorry for the lonely Boob, and invites him to join them aboard the submarine. They arrive at the Foothills of the Headlands, where they are separated from the submarine and Old Fred (\"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\"). They then find themselves in the Sea of Holes, an expanse of flat surfaces with many holes. Jeremy is kidnapped by a Blue Meanie, and the group finds their way to Pepperland.\n\nReuniting with Old Fred and reviving the Lord Mayor, they look upon the now-miserable, grey landscape. The Beatles dress up as Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band and steal some instruments. The four rally the land to rebellion (\"[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (song)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]\"). The [[Chief Blue Meanie]] retaliates by sending out the Dreadful Flying Glove, but John defeats by singing (\"[[All You Need is Love]]\"). Pepperland is restored to colour as its flowers re-bloom and its residents revive. The original Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band are released, and join the Beatles in combating the Meanies' multi-headed dog (\"[[Hey Bulldog]]\"). Jeremy performs some \"transformation magic\" on the Chief Blue Meanie, causing the Meanie to bloom roses and sadly concede defeat. John extends an offer of friendship, and the Chief Blue Meanie has a change of heart and accepts. An enormous party ensues (\"[[It's All Too Much]]\").\n\nThe real Beatles then appear in [[live-action]], and playfully show off souvenirs from the events of the film. George has the submarine's motor, Paul has \"a little 'love'\", and Ringo has \"half a hole\" in his pocket (having supposedly given the other half to Jeremy). Ringo points out John looking through a telescope, which prompts Paul to ask what he sees. John replies that \"newer and bluer Meanies have been sighted within the vicinity of this theatre\" and claims there is only one way to go out: \"Singing!\" The four oblige with a short reprise of \"All Together Now\", which ends with translations of the song's title in various languages appearing in sequence on the screen.\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[John Clive]] as [[John Lennon|John]]\n* [[Geoffrey Hughes]] as [[Paul McCartney|Paul]]\n* Peter Batten as [[George Harrison|George]] ''(uncredited)''\n* [[Paul Angelis]] as Opening Narrator / [[Chief Blue Meanie]] / [[Ringo Starr|Ringo]] / George ''(additional dialogue)''\n* [[Dick Emery]] as Max / Lord Mayor / [[Jeremy Hillary Boob]]\n* [[Lance Percival]] as \"Young/Old\" Fred\n\n'''<small>Sources:<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0063823/fullcredits#cast Yellow Submarine (1968) \u2013 Full cast and crew<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[[Apple Corps]], 2012.</ref></small>'''\n\n'''Cast notes'''\n* According to the special features section of the ''Yellow Submarine'' home media release, Peter Batten provided the voice of George for about the first half of the film. Before he finished recording for the film, he was discovered to be a [[deserter]] from the [[British Army of the Rhine]] in [[West Germany]], and was arrested. His part was completed by Angelis, who was also the voice of Ringo and the Chief Blue Meanie.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/1999/aug/24/artsfeatures2|last=Espiner|first=Mark|title=The Fake Four | location=London |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 August 1999|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Percival also provided the voices of Paul and Ringo for the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] TV cartoon series ''[[The Beatles (TV series)|The Beatles]]''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[The Beatles]] were not enthusiastic about participating in a new motion picture, having been dissatisfied with their second feature film, ''[[Help! (film)|Help!]]'' (1965), directed by [[Richard Lester]]. However, they saw an animated film as a favourable way to complete their commitment to [[United Artists]] for a third film. Many fans have assumed that the cartoon did not satisfy the contract, but ''[[Let It Be (film)|Let It Be]]'' (1970) was the film not connected to the original three-picture deal.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hieronimus|first1=Dr Robert|title=Inside the Yellow Submarine|publisher=Krause|isbn=0-87349-360-5|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\nThe Beatles make a live-action [[cameo appearance]] in the final scene, which was filmed on 25 January 1968, shortly before the band's [[The Beatles in India|trip to India]]. This was done primarily to fulfill their contractual obligation to United Artists to actually appear in the film. The cameo was originally intended to feature a post-production psychedelic background and effects, but because of time and budget constraints, a blank, black background remained in the final film. While Starr and McCartney still looked the same as their animated counterparts, Lennon's and Harrison's physical appearances had changed by the time the cameo was shot. Both were clean-shaven, and Lennon had begun to grow his hair longer with accompanying mutton-chop [[sideburns]].\n\nThe original story was written by Lee Minoff, based on the song by John Lennon and Paul McCartney, and the screenplay was penned by four collaborators including [[Erich Segal]]. George Harrison's character's recurring line \"It's all in the mind\" is taken from ''[[The Goon Show]]''.\n\nAs with many motion-picture [[Musical film|musicals]], the music takes precedence over the actual plot, and most of the story is a series of [[set piece]]s designed to present Beatles music set to various images, in a form reminiscent of [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' (and foreshadowing the rise of music videos and MTV thirteen years later). {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Nonetheless, the film still presents a modern-day [[fairy tale]] representing the values of its intended [[hippie]] audience.\n\nThe dialogue is littered with [[pun]]s, [[double entendre]]s and Beatles in-jokes. In the DVD [[Audio commentary|commentary track]], production supervisor John Coates states that many of these lines were written by Liverpudlian poet [[Roger McGough]], though he received no credit in the film.\n\nIn the DVD commentary track, Coates states that the Meanies were always intended to be coloured blue. However, Millicent McMillan recalls that the Blue Meanies were originally supposed to be red, or even purple, but when [[Heinz Edelmann]]'s assistant accidentally changed the colours, the film's characters took on a different meaning.<ref name=\"Hieronimus-hidden\">{{cite web | last = Hieronimus | first = Robert R. | date = 11 September 1999 | url = http://www.21stcenturyradio.com/yellowsub/billboard.html | title = The Hidden Stories Behind Yellow Submarine | work = Billboard | accessdate = 19 April 2009}}</ref> Coates acknowledges in the commentary that the \"are you Bluish? You don't look Bluish\" joke in the film is a pun on the then-contemporary expression \"you don't look Jewish\", but that it was not intended to be derogatory.\n\n===Animation===\nThe Beatles' animated personas were based on their appearance in the promotional film for the song \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\", with the exception of Paul being without his moustache. The film also includes several references to songs not included in the soundtrack, including \"[[A Day in the Life]]\", the lyrics of which are referenced in the \"Sea of Holes\" scene; the orchestral breaks earlier in the film are also taken from the song.\n\nNational and foreign animators were assembled by TVC. American animators [[Robert Balser]] and [[Jack Stokes (director)|Jack Stokes]] were hired as the film's animation directors.<ref name=awn>{{cite news|first=Jennifer|last=Wolfe|title='Yellow Submarine' Animation Director Robert Balser Passes at 88 |url=http://www.awn.com/news/yellow-submarine-animation-director-robert-balser-passes-88  |work=[[Animation World Network]] |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=thr>{{cite news|first=Mike|last=Barnes|title=Robert Balser, Animation Director on 'Yellow Submarine,' Dies at 88 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/robert-balser-dead-yellow-submarine-852980  |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=7 January 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Charlie Jenkins, one of the film's key creative directors, was responsible for the entire \"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\" sequence, as well as the submarine travel from Liverpool, through London, to splashdown. Jenkins also was responsible for \"Only a Northern Song\" in the Sea of Science, plus much of the multi-image sequences. A large crew of skilled animators, including (in alphabetical order) Alan Ball, [[Ron Campbell (animator)|Ron Campbell]], John Challis, Hester Coblentz, Geoff Collins, Rich Cox, Duane Crowther, Tony Cuthbert, Malcolm Draper, [[Paul Driessen (animator)|Paul Driessen]], Cam Ford, Norm Drew, Tom Halley, Dick Horne, Arthur Humberstone, Dennis Hunt, [[Greg Irons]], [[Dianne Jackson]], [[Anne Jolliffe]], Dave Livesey, Reg Lodge, Geoff Loynes, Lawrence Moorcroft, Ted Percival, Mike Pocock, [[Gerald Potterton]], and Peter Tupy, were responsible for bringing the animated Beatles to life. The background work was executed by artists under the direction of [[Alison de Vere]] and Millicent McMillan, who were both background supervisors. Ted Lewis and Chris Miles were responsible for animation cleanup.\n\n[[George Dunning]], who also worked on [[The Beatles (TV series)|the Beatles cartoon series]], was the overall director for the film, supervising over 200 artists for 11 months. \"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\" was Dunning's idea, which he turned over to Bill Sewell, who delivered more than thirty minutes of [[Rotoscoping|rotoscoped]] images. By that time, Dunning was unavailable, and Bob Balser, with the help of Arne Gustafson, edited the material to its sequence length in the film.\n\nThe animation design of ''Yellow Submarine'' has sometimes been incorrectly attributed to famous psychedelic [[pop art]] artist of the era [[Peter Max]], but the film's art director was [[Heinz Edelmann]]. Edelmann, along with his contemporary [[Milton Glaser]], pioneered the psychedelic style for which Max would later become famous, but according to Edelmann and producer Al Brodax, as quoted in the book ''Inside the Yellow Submarine'' by Hieronimus and Cortner, Max had nothing to do with the production of ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref name=\"Hieronimus-inside\">{{Cite book | last =Hieronimus | first =Robert |author2=Laura Cortner | title =Inside the Yellow Submarine | year =2002 | publisher =Krause Publications | location =Iola, Wisconsin, USA | isbn =0-87349-360-5 | page =81 | chapter =| chapterurl =| quote =}}</ref>\n \nEdelmann's surreal visual style contrasts greatly with the efforts of [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] and other animated Hollywood films that had been previously released at the time. The film uses a style of [[limited animation]]. It also paved the way for [[Terry Gilliam]]'s animations for ''[[Do Not Adjust Your Set]]'' and ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' (particularly the ''Eleanor Rigby'' sequence), as well as the ''[[Schoolhouse Rock]]'' vignettes for ABC and similar-looking animation in early seasons of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' and ''[[The Electric Company]]''. (Only one of the animation staff of ''Yellow Submarine'', Ron Campbell, contributed subsequent animation to  [[Sesame Workshop|Children's Television Workshop]].)\n\n===Music===\nIn addition to the 1966 title song \"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\", several complete or excerpted songs, four previously unreleased, were used in the film. The songs included \"[[All Together Now]]\", \"[[It's All Too Much]]\" (written by Harrison), \"[[Baby, You're a Rich Man]]\" (which had first appeared as the [[B-side]] to \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\" in June 1967), \"[[Only a Northern Song]]\" (a Harrison composition originally recorded during sessions for ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]])'' and \"[[Hey Bulldog]]\". Written by Lennon, this last track was cut from the film before it opened in the US. \"Hey Bulldog\" was restored for the US theatrical and home video reissue in 1999. The four new songs used on the soundtrack album were not considered of high enough quality for appearance on a \"regular\" Beatles album.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nThe film's instrumental music was an orchestral score composed and arranged by [[George Martin]]. One of the film's cues, heard after the main title credits, was originally recorded during sessions for \"[[Good Night (Beatles song)|Good Night]]\" (a track on ''[[The Beatles (album)|The Beatles]]'', also known as the \"White Album\") and would have been used as the introduction to Ringo Starr's White Album composition \"[[Don't Pass Me By]]\". The same cue was later released as \"[[A Beginning]]\" on the 1996 Beatles compilation ''[[Anthology 3]]''.\n\n==Musical numbers==\n:All tracks written by [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]] except where noted.\n\n:Track start and end time is indicated in [[hour|hrs]]:[[minute|mins]]:[[second|secs]]. These are approximated because the songs are embedded in the film plot and cannot be strictly separated.\n\n# 0:00:21\u20130:02:15: \"Introduction Story\" music by [[George Martin]]\n# 0:07:55\u20130:10:40: \"[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]\"\n# 0:10:40\u20130:13:30: \"[[Eleanor Rigby]]\"\n# 0:19:00\u20130:19:55: \"[[Love You To]]\" ([[George Harrison]]) (excerpt, played during George's entrance)\n# 0:22:30\u20130:23:05: \"[[A Day in the Life]]\" (excerpt, orchestral swell, starting as the submarine takes off)\n# 0:23:25\u20130:25:55: \"[[All Together Now]]\"\n# 0:28:20\u20130:31:15: \"[[When I'm Sixty-Four]]\"\n# 0:31:30\u20130:34:30: \"[[Only a Northern Song]]\" (Harrison)\n# 0:43:15\u20130:46:15: \"[[Nowhere Man (song)|Nowhere Man]]\"\n# 0:48:00\u20130:51:30: \"[[Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds]]\"\n# 0:54:30\u20130:54:50: \"Yellow Submarine\" (a short vocal excerpt when Ringo finds the green hole that leads to Pepperland)\n# 0:56:15\u20130:56:25: \"[[Think for Yourself]]\" (Harrison) (short excerpt, a line is sung [[a cappella]] to revive the Lord Mayor)\n# 1:06:35\u20131:08:50: \"[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (song)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]\"\n# 1:08:50\u20131:09:05: \"[[With a Little Help from My Friends]]\" (short excerpt, directly following \"Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band\" without interruption, just as on the [[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|1967 album of the same name]])\n# 1:11:45\u20131:15:05: \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\"\n# 1:16:30\u20131:16:40: \"[[Baby, You're a Rich Man]]\" (excerpt, played as Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band are, thanks to Ringo's \"hole in [his] pocket\", set free from the anti-music bubble; the recording of the song is expanded for the American-released version, and the scene with the expansion of the recording of the song leads to a scene that replaces the anti-climactic \"Hey Bulldog\".){{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n# 1:17:25\u20131:21:00: \"[[Hey Bulldog]]\" (originally shown only in Europe before the film's 1999 restoration)\n# 1:24:15\u20131:27:15: \"[[It's All Too Much]]\" (Harrison)\n# 1:27:15\u20131:29:00: \"[[All Together Now]]\" (accompanied by images of the real Beatles singing, numbers and letters, and \"all together now\" translated in various languages)\n\n;First soundtrack album\n{{Main|Yellow Submarine (album)}}\nThe original soundtrack album comprised the four new Beatles songs, two other Beatles songs (the title song and \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\"), and orchestral pieces by [[George Martin]].\n\nThe orchestral pieces were also used in the short [[NASA]] ''[[Apollo 9]]'' mission films, which NASA made for every mission.<ref>{{Citation|title=Apollo 9 : space duet of SpiderGumdrop|url=http://archive.org/details/Apollo9SpaceDuetOfSpidergumdrop|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>\n\n;Second soundtrack album\n{{Main|Yellow Submarine Songtrack}}\nAnother soundtrack was released in 1999 that contained all of the Beatles' songs from the film except \"A Day in the Life\".\n\n==Reception==\n''Yellow Submarine'' received widespread critical acclaim. Released in the midst of the [[Psychedelia|psychedelic]] pop culture of the 1960s, the film drew in moviegoers both for its lush, wildly creative images and its soundtrack of Beatles songs. The film was distributed worldwide by [[United Artists]] in two versions. The version shown in [[Europe]] included an extra musical number, \"Hey Bulldog\", heard in the final third of the film. For release in the United States, the number was replaced with alternative animation because of time constraints. It was felt that, at the time, American audiences would grow tired from the length of the film. Despite the Beatles connection, the film was not a commercial success.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Silver |first1=David |title=The Compleat Beatles DVD |work=The Compleat Beatles |agency=Delilah Films, Inc. |issue=First release |publisher=MGM/UA Entertainment Co. |date=1982}}</ref>\nThe film realized receipts of more than $992,000 USD in the US and more than $280,000 USD internationally.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine - Financial Information |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Yellow-Submarine#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1896121857/weekend/ |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDB.com |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> For reference, the top-grossing films for 1968 were in excess of $50M in the domestic market alone.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Funny Girl (1968) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Funny-Girl-%281968%29#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=2001: a space odyssey |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/2001-A-Space-Odyssey#tab=summary |website=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Informatioon Services, LLC |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film currently holds a 97% approval rating based on 58 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9/10.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |title=Yellow Submarine |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beatles_the_yellow_submarine |website=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The website's critical consensus states: \"A joyful, phantasmagoric blend of colorful animation and the music of the Beatles, ''Yellow Submarine'' is delightful (and occasionally melancholy) family fare.\"<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beatles_the_yellow_submarine/ | title =Yellow Submarine (1968) | publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate =29 June 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 78 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/yellow-submarine |title=Yellow Submarine Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rights and distribution==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nOf all the Beatles films released by United Artists, ''Yellow Submarine'' been the only one to which UA retained the rights, leading up to its purchase by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1981. In 2005, [[Sony Pictures|Sony Pictures Entertainment]] led a consortium that purchased MGM and UA. SPE handled theatrical distribution for MGM until 2012. [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] was responsible for home video distribution when the most recent home video release went out of print.\n\nFor the 50th anniversary of the movie in 2018, it was screened in the UK and Ireland for one day on 8 July 2018, and in the US from 8 July 2018.<ref name=\"Jon Blistein\">{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-beatles-yellow-submarine-returning-to-theaters-630183/ | work=Rolling Stone | author=Jon Blistein | title=The Beatles' 'Yellow Submarine' Returning to Theaters | date=4 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/iconic-beatles-film-heading-back-uk-cinemas-one-night-2219667 | work=Rolling Stone | author= Nick Reilly| title=This iconic Beatles film is heading back to UK cinemas for its 50th anniversary| date=15 January 2018}}</ref> [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] negotiated exclusive streaming rights to the film via its [[Prime Video]] service, starting 13 July 2018 in the UK, the US, Canada, Germany, Spain, France and Italy under a deal with [[Apple Corps]]. The companies declined to disclose the length of Amazon's exclusive rights.<ref name=\"Todd Spangler\">{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/beatles-yellow-submarine-amazon-prime-video-1202872708/ | work=Variety| author=  Todd Spangler| title=The Beatles' 'Yellow Submarine' Now Streaming Exclusively on Amazon Prime Video| date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\nWith the dawn of the home-video era came an opportunity to release ''Yellow Submarine'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]]. However, it was held up by United Artists for some years over music-rights issues.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Coinciding with the [[Compact disc|CD]] release of the soundtrack album, United Artists issued the film on home video on 28 August, 1987. To the disappointment of fans in the UK, the film was presented in its US theatrical version, thereby omitting the \"Hey Bulldog\" scene.<ref>{{cite book|first=Keith|last=Badman|year=2001|title=The Beatles Diary Volume 2: After the Break-Up 1970\u20132001|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-7119-8307-6|pp=390\u201391}}</ref> The video was discontinued around 1990, and for many years copies of the original VHS issue were considered [[collectable]]s.\n\nOn 14 September 1999, then-rights holders [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and Apple reissued the film for the first time on [[DVD]] and VHS using restoration techniques of the time. The sound was remixed to [[Dolby 5.1]], and the film was re-edited to its European theatrical version, with the \"Hey Bulldog\" number restored. This version (released through MGM Home Entertainment) went out of print once the rights reverted to Apple Corps.\n\n===Restoration===\nOn 20 March 2012, Apple Corps announced that the film had been restored by hand for [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] release on 28 May 2012 (29 May in North America), later delayed one week to 4 June 2012 (5 June in North America). The company stated: \"The film's soundtrack album will be reissued on CD on the same date. The film has been restored in 4K digital resolution for the first time \u2013 all done by hand, frame by frame.\" The delicate restoration was supervised by Paul Rutan Jr and his team, which included Chris Dusendschon, Rayan Raghuram and Randy Walker.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Re-release of Yellow Submarine \u2013 Exclusive Q & A with Paul Rutan Jr.|url = http://www.21stcenturyradio.com/yellowsub/PaulRutanJr_Hieronimus_Restoring_Yellow_Sub.html|website = 21stcenturyradio|accessdate = 28 May 2015}}</ref> No automated software was used to clean up the film's repaired and digitised photo-chemical elements. The work was done by hand, a single frame at a time, by 40 to 60 trained digital artists, over several months.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Yellow Submarine Gets a Film Restoration and 4K Remaster|url = http://www.studiodaily.com/2012/06/yellow-submarine-gets-a-film-restoration-and-4k-remaster/|website = Studio Daily|accessdate = 28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the DVD and Blu-ray re-release, the restored version also received a limited theatrical run in May 2012.\n\nFor the 50th anniversary of the film, the soundtrack and score were remixed in 5.1 stereo surround sound at [[Abbey Road Studios]] by mix engineer Peter Cobbin.<ref name=\"Jon Blistein\"/>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}{{main|Yellow Submarine (album)}}\nOn 14 September 1999, United Artists and [[Apple Records]] digitally remixed the audio of the film for a highly successful theatrical and home video re-release. Though the visuals were not digitally restored, a new transfer was done after cleaning the original film negative and rejuvenating the colour. A [[Yellow Submarine Songtrack|soundtrack album for this version]] was also released, which featured the first extensive digital stereo remixes of Beatles material.\n\nThe previous DVD release also featured a music-only audio track, without spoken dialogue, leaving only the music and the songs.\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2018}}\n* [[1968 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]] Special Award\n* 1969 [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation|Best Dramatic Presentation]] (nominated)\n* 1970 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Original Score Written for a Motion Picture or a Television Special]] (nominated)\n\n== Cancelled remake ==\nIn August 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Walt Disney Pictures]] and filmmaker [[Robert Zemeckis]] were negotiating to produce a [[3D film|3D]] [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[remake]] of the film. [[Motion capture]] was to be used, as with Zemeckis' previous animated films ''[[The Polar Express (film)|The Polar Express]]'' (2004), ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'' (2006), ''[[Beowulf (2007 film)|Beowulf]]'' (2007) and ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' (2009). ''Variety'' also indicated that Disney hoped to release the film in time for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]].<ref>Fleming, Michael. \"[https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118007485?refCatId=13 Disney, Zemeckis to board 'Submarine']\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', 19 August 2009.</ref> Disney and Apple Corps officially announced the remake at the inaugural D23 Expo on 11 September 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonzone.net/news/articles/31091/disney-and-apple-corps-ltd.-confirm-yellow-submarine-remake |title=Animation News Discussion Cartoon Community \u2013 toonzone news |publisher=News.toonzone.net |accessdate=9 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913104045/http://www.toonzone.net/2009/09/disney-and-apple-corps-ltd-confirm-yellow-submarine-remake/%23.UFG4GqjLdRw |archivedate=13 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\nComedian [[Peter Serafinowicz]] was cast to voice Paul, [[Dean Lennox Kelly]] as John, [[Cary Elwes]] as George and [[Adam Campbell (actor)|Adam Campbell]] as Ringo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=26687 |title=Peter Serafinowicz IS Paul McCartney! |work=Empire  |accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref> California-based Beatles [[Tribute act|tribute band]] [[The Fab Four (tribute)|The Fab Four]] was cast to perform the performance capture animation for the animated Beatles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/01/12/actors-tribute-band-cast-as-beatles-in-zemeckis-yellow-submarine-remake/ |title=Actors, Tribute Band Cast as Beatles in Zemeckis' \"Yellow Submarine\" Remake |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |work=Rolling Stone |date=12 January 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117024516/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2010/01/12/actors-tribute-band-cast-as-beatles-in-zemeckis-yellow-submarine-remake/ |archivedate=17 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gibson.com/en%2Dus/Lifestyle/News/yellow%2Dsubmarine%2D0113/ | title=Main Cast Selected For Beatles' Yellow Submarine Remake | first=Russell | last=Hall | publisher=gibson.com | date=13 January 2010 | accessdate=13 January 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603235918/http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/News/yellow-submarine-0113/ | archivedate=3 June 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Disney closed Zemeckis' digital film studio [[ImageMovers|ImageMovers Digital]] after unsatisfactory box-office performance of ''A Christmas Carol''.<ref name=\"gump\" /> On 14 March 2011, Disney abandoned the project, citing the disastrous opening weekend results of [[Simon Wells]]' ''[[Mars Needs Moms]]''. Criticism toward motion-capture technology was also a factor.<ref name=\"gump\">Kit, Borys. [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/15/us-yellowsubmarine-idUSTRE72E0ED20110315 Disney torpedoes Zemeckis' \"Yellow Submarine\"] ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' (14 March 2011).</ref>\n\nAfter its cancellation at Disney, Zemeckis tried to pitch the remake to other studios. By December 2012, Zemeckis expressed that he had lost interest in the project, stating: \"That would have been great to bring the Beatles back to life. But it's probably better not to be remade \u2013 you're always behind the 8-ball when do you{{sic}} a remake.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.slashfilm.com/robert-zemeckis-gives-up-on-the-yellow-submarine-remake/|title= Robert Zemeckis Gives Up On the 'Yellow Submarine' Remake|work=Slash Film|last1=Han|first1=Angie|date=27 December 2012|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:Corgi Classics Beatles Yellow Submarine 1999.jpg|thumb|In the late 1960s, Corgi Classics Ltd. (formerly known as Corgi Toys) issued a licensed die-cast toy model of Yellow Submarine. In 1999, this particular model was re-issued as a collector\u2019s item (as shown).]]\n* In the 1993 episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' titled \"[[Last Exit to Springfield]]\", [[Lisa Simpson]], under [[anesthetic]], has a dream sequence highly reminiscent of the film.<ref>{{cite book|last=Erickson|first=Hal|year=2005|title=Television Cartoon Shows: An Illustrated Encyclopedia, 1949\u20142003|volume=2|edition=2nd|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|page=746|isbn=978-0-7864-2099-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/28/arts/television/simpsons-history-season-30-timeline.html|title='The Simpsons' at 30: Six Era-Defining Episodes|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|date=28 September 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-simpsons-oral-history-of-last-exit-to-springfield-the-best-episode-ever/|title='The Simpsons' Oral History of 'Last Exit to Springfield,' The Best Episode Ever|last=Welk|first=Brian|date=8 March 2018|website=[[TheWrap]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Professional wrestler [[The Blue Meanie]] derived his name and persona from the villains of the film.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Oliver|first1=Greg|last2=Johnson|first2=Steven|year=2019|title=The Pro Wrestling Hall of Fame: The Storytellers (From the Terrible Turk to Twitter)|publisher=[[ECW Press]]|isbn=978-1770415027}}</ref>\n* The 2001 episode of ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' titled \"Meet the Beat Alls\", which contains numerous Beatles references, briefly features cameos of the band members' likenesses from ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/dont-beat/|title=If That Don't Beat All|last=Mallory|first=Michael|date=2 January 2014|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2007 film ''[[Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story]]'' features an animated acid trip sequence that parodies ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/ae/2007/12/20/Movie-Review-The-Dewey-Cox-Story/stories/200712200360|title=Movie Review: 'The Dewey Cox Story'|last=Vancheri|first=Barbara|date=20 December 2007|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/03/movies/yellow-submarine-beatles-50th-anniversary.html|title='Yellow Submarine' to Arrive in Theaters for Its 50th Anniversary|last=Chow|first=Andrew R.|date=3 April 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Olson|first=Christopher J.|year=2018|title=100 Greatest Cult Films|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|page=257|isbn=978-1442208223}}</ref>\n* The third ''[[Futurama]]'' film, ''[[Futurama: Bender's Game|Bender's Game]]'' (2008), makes visual references to ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.avclub.com/futurama-bender-s-game-1798184766|title=Futurama: Bender's Game|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=3 September 2015|work=[[The A. V. Club]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2014, apparel company [[Vans]] released a series of shoes based on ''Yellow Submarine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-beatles-team-with-vans-for-yellow-submarine-shoes-242240/|title=The Beatles Team With Vans for 'Yellow Submarine' Shoes|last=Grow|first=Kory|date=23 January 2014|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2016, for the 50th anniversary of the original song's release, the die-cast toy car brand [[Hot Wheels]] released a miniature replica of the Yellow Submarine from the film, as well as an assortment of six toy cars featuring imagery from the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/06/08/beatles-yellow-submarine-50th-anniversary-hot-wheels/|title=Hot Wheels unveil Beatles' Yellow Submarine 50th anniversary collection \u2014 exclusive|last=Slead|first=Evan|date=8 June 2016|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n* In 2016, [[Lego Ideas]] released a ''Yellow Submarine'' Lego set that includes minifigures of the four Beatles and Jeremy Hillary Boob, along with the submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-beatles/97065|title=Lego unveil new Yellow Submarine set with The Beatles|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|date=12 October 2016|website=[[NME]]|access-date=25 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015034333/https://www.nme.com/news/the-beatles/97065|archive-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n*In the 2019 [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'', [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony Stark]] jokingly refers to his shipmate [[Nebula (comics)|Nebula]] as a \"Blue Meanie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/4/30/18619514/avengers-endgame-22-little-moments-that-added-up-to-greatness|title='Avengers: Endgame': 22 little moments that added up to greatness|last=Roeper|first=Richard|author-link=Richard Roeper|date=30 April 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/04/avengers-endgame-easter-eggs.html|title=An Exhaustive List of All the Easter Eggs and Comic Book References in Avengers: Endgame|last=Grebey|first=James|date=29 April 2019|website=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Animation|Film}}\n* [[The Beatles in film]]\n* [[List of animated feature-length films]]\n* [[List of fictional ships#Film|List of fictional submarines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.thebeatles.com/film/yellow-submarine}}\n* {{IMDb title|0063823|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{tcmdb title|96403|Yellow Submarine}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|beatles_the_yellow_submarine|Yellow Submarine}}\n* [https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-yellow-submarine-1968 ''Yellow Submarine'' movie review] by [[Roger Ebert]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/brunel/A295562 h2g2 Yellow Submarine \u2013 the Film Edited Guide Entry]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/23/arts/design/23edelmann.html \"Heinz Edelmann, 'Yellow Submarine' Artist, Dies at 75\"], ''The New York Times''\n* [https://www.popmatters.com/pm/post/110163-its-all-too-much-robert-zemeckis-proposed-yellow-submarine-remake/ Proposed ''Yellow Submarine'' remake]\n\n{{Yellow Submarine}}\n{{Beatles filmography and videography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yellow Submarine}}\n[[Category:The Beatles' Yellow Submarine]]\n[[Category:1968 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1968 animated films]]\n[[Category:1960s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:British musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:British musical films]]\n[[Category:Animation based on real people]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:British rock music films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Beatles]]\n[[Category:Films associated with the Beatles]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of The Beatles]]\n[[Category:Films based on songs]]\n[[Category:Films set in a fictional country]]\n[[Category:Films set in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Rotoscoped films]]\n[[Category:Submarine films]]\n[[Category:Apple Films films]]\n[[Category:United Artists animated films]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Psychedelia]]\n[[Category:British animated films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n", "name_user": "MatthewHoobin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Linking and formatting.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yellow_Submarine_(film)"}
{"title_page": "FC Belshina Bobruisk", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = FC Belshina Bobruisk\n| image    = FC Belshyna Babruisk.png\n| fullname = Football Club Belshina\n| nickname = \n| founded  = 1976\n| ground   = [[Spartak Stadium (Bobruisk)|Spartak Stadium]], [[Bobruisk]]\n| capacity = 3,700\n| chairman = Mikhail Bondarenko\n| manager  = [[Eduard Gradoboyev]]\n| league   = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season   = [[2019 Belarusian First League|2019]]\n| position = [[Belarusian First League]], 1st (promoted)\n| website  = http://www.fcbelshina.by\n| pattern_la1 = |pattern_b1 = _hb1819h |pattern_ra1 = |pattern_sh1 = |pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1 = FF0000 |body1 = FF0000 |rightarm1 = FF0000 |shorts1 = FFFFFF |socks1 = FF0000\n| pattern_la2 =_redbull1718h |pattern_b2 = _redbull1718h |pattern_ra2 =_redbull1718h |pattern_sh2 = _whitesides |pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = DDDDDD |body2 = DDDDDD |rightarm2 = DDDDDD |shorts2 = FFFFFF |socks2 = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Belshina Bobruisk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \"\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0448\u044b\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\"}}, ''FK Belshyna Babruisk'') is a [[Belarus]]ian [[association football|football]] club based in [[Bobruisk]]. The team has won one [[Belarusian Premier League]] title, as well as 3 [[Belarusian Cup]] titles, in post-Soviet Belarus.\n\n==History of the club and football in Bobruisk==\nThe city of Bobruisk was represented by its football team as early as 1920s, when in 1926 a collective football team of Bobruisk city won the Belarusian football championship. Winning the 1926, Bobruisk football team became the first from a provincial city that won the republican competitions. Until 1958, it was the only achievement of the Bobruisk football. In 1958, ''Spartak Bobruisk'' became a champion of Belarus donating the second title to the Bobruisk city football.\n\nIn 1972 and 1973, ''Stroitel Bobruisk'' also won a title of the champion of Belarus.\n\nThe current club was founded in 1976 as '''Shinnik Bobruisk'''. Since the inception the team was attached to and later sponsored by local tire manufacturing company [[Belshina]]. The club spent most of Soviet-era seasons in the [[Belarusian SSR]] league (with a couple of seasons in the [[Mogilev Oblast]] league). Shinnik won the league title twice (in 1978 and 1987) and also won the Belarusian SSR Cup in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbelshina.by/istoriya/kratkiy-ocherk-razvitiya-futbola-v-bobruyske.php|title=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0435|author=|date=|work=fcbelshina.by|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Shinnik joined the [[Belarusian First League]] and in 1994, they were promoted to the [[Belarusian Premier League|Premier League]]. In 1996, they were renamed to '''Belshina Bobruisk'''. The club's most successful seasons came in the late 1990s and early 2000s. Belshina won the champions title in 2001, finished as runners-up in 1997 and won the[[Belarusian Cup]] three times (1997, 1999, 2001).\n\n===Name changes===\n*1976: Founded as Shinnik Bobruisk\n*1996: Renamed to Belshina Bobruisk\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Belarusian Premier League]]'''\n** ''Winners (1):'' [[2001 Belarusian Premier League|2001]]\n** ''Runners-up (1):'' [[1997 Belarusian Premier League|1997]]\n** ''3rd place (2):'' [[1996 Belarusian Premier League|1996]], [[1998 Belarusian Premier League|1998]]\n* '''[[Belarusian Cup]]'''\n** ''Winners (3):'' [[1996\u201397 Belarusian Cup|1997]], [[1998\u201399 Belarusian Cup|1999]], [[2000\u201301 Belarusian Cup|2001]]\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of April 2020'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbelshina.by/komanda/osnovnoy-sostav/|title=\u041e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432|website=www.fcbelshina.by}}</ref>\n\n{{Fs s